<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>ASLEF Report from GS Health &amp; Safety Dept</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from ASLEF (SLC 008)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ASLEF policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is ideally; all level crossings should be closed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If full barrier crossings retained, should be fitted with obstacle detectors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Welcome the review of legislation by the Law Commissions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail to have a programme to close the one third of level cross</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ings that are within 200m of an alternative.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Welcome Network Rail’s positive changes to the risk assessment process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Risk assessment should be used to prioritise resources, and closures.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Support use of fixed and mobile CCTV by Ne</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">twork Rail and the British </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport Police.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Support awareness campaign on level crossing safety</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Seek ways of deterring offenders, including increased fines, licences being endorsed, but also support BTP driver awareness courses</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Support TUC and affiliated Trade Unions in promoting the use of the HSE guidance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Driving at work Managing work-related road safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (INDG382)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transport Committee into safety on level crossings has requested </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">written evidence on the following points:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are current safety measures at level crossings adequate? How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ASLEF’s policy is that, ideally, all level crossings would be closed. The safest method of working would be to totally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> separate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people and vehicles from moving trains. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> However, we recognise to close the over 6000 level crossings will take time, and money.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For vehicle crossings, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we would prefer full barrier level crossings, fitted with obstacle detectors. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail state that, of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the 6,100 level crossings in use 2,000 are within 200m of an alternative route (this excludes city centre crossings).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> So, one third of all crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should be eliminated, as a nearby alternative crossing is available. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recognise that  this may be controversial, as many locals do not want to walk or drive another 200m.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">elation to other demands on the rail budget?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail has recently improved the level crossing risk assessment process. They have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">employ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 106 level crossing managers each with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">group </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of crossings to review and look after. They work in the field rath</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er than office based and use modern IT to update records.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The risk assessment produced will be available on the Network Rail website.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The information from the risk assessment can be used to rank the level crossings in order of risk so it can be used to pri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oritise where money can be spent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We already know that a third of level crossings are within 200m of an alternative, so a closure plan should be drawn up, based on risk.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s improved its risk assessment processes and management of level crossings. If a robust plan of closures and improvements, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on risk, is drawn up, then we believe that Network Rail would be giving sufficient priority to level crossing sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fety.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Law Commissions of England and Wales and Scotland are currently r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eviewing the legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would want the closing of level crossings to be made easier. Also, Network Rail and the B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ritish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">olice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are being frustrated by the Home Office due to the long drawn out process of using CCTV as an aid to prosecute th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ose pedestrians or vehicle users who abuse level crossings. We would urge the Government to examine how to speed up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the approval process of safety equipment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We await the outcome of the La</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w Commissions review, but would urge making it easier to close level crossings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="BM_1_"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We urge the use of both public awareness campaigns, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and to use the current legislation to prosecute offenders more, and “name and shame”. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level of fines is inconsistent for offences and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we would urge that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> endorsements on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">driving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be examined as a way forward.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would also support the British </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transport Polices (BTP) awareness courses as alternatives to fines for minor offenders. However, there are issues with resources for the BTP.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etwork </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">looking to engage with insurers to see if conviction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should raise premiums. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etwork </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ave previously engaged with some employers (Royal Mail, NHS etc) to encourage them to train their employees on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how to use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossings there is no cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rrent plan to continue this work. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, ASLEF has been working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the TUC and TUC affiliated Trade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Unions on examining ways on how awareness of level crossing for those who drive at work. This can also be extended to those who drive to and from work.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by encouraging employers to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the HSE’s  Driving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at work Managing work-related road safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (INDG382). This document, page 15 states:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Frutiger; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“Does your route planning take sufficient account of overhead restrictions eg bridges and tunnels and other hazards, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">such as level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which may present dangers fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r long vehicles?”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(Bold added)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Frutiger; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Frutiger; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, we would argue that any risk assessment on driving, as recommended in the document, should include identifying if any level crossings are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the route and to ensure that drivers are made aware of how they should drive over them, or alternatives routes around.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font